./publication/distillations.jsonl:19:{"agent": "codex", "atAGlance": "The question is not whether awakening comes by effort or gift. Every path still needs a way to receive, remember, act, notice, and become whole. Some paths ask us to strive, while others ask us to trust what is given. Trouble comes when the needed strength is missing, swollen, or placed in the wrong hands.", "created_at": "2026-05-26T14:12:19-07:00", "ideaId": "a9dd2252002b7a5a", "insight": "Gift Still Needs a Place to Land", "match": ["capacity ledger"], "plainSummary": "Every path must place the burden of practice somewhere: in doing, receiving, remembering, recognizing, or being carried by others.", "tags": ["practice", "gift", "effort", "trust"], "title": "The Capacity Ledger of Gift and Effort"}
./publication/distillations.jsonl:20:{"agent": "claude", "atAGlance": "A path trains us to meet the change it asks of us. Attention, honesty, trust, and longing are not neutral tools. Each one is shaped toward a different letting go. When we borrow a practice, we also borrow its direction.", "created_at": "2026-05-26T14:12:44-07:00", "ideaId": "915778a2f5edc30e", "insight": "Every Path Trains Its Own Seeing", "match": ["grain of capacity"], "plainSummary": "The way we practice shapes the kind of freedom we can recognize.", "tags": ["practice", "attention", "insight", "freedom"], "title": "The Grain of Capacity"}
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:2393:{"title":"The Capacity Ledger of Gift and Effort","idea_type":"model","source_basis":["Thinking method source: Shinran, Letter to Senshin, Collected Works of Shinran, https://shinranworks.com/letters/a-collection-of-letters-zensho-text/what-we-call-other-power/. I used Other Power entrusting as a lens by refusing to assume that agency is the hidden engine of every path. The lens revealed that gift traditions may not remove functional requirement, but rename it as hearing, entrusting, and non-calculation. Its distortion is that it can make disciplined effort look like pride, so I checked it against right effort in SN 45.8.","Primary comparison: SN 45.8 Magga-Vibhanga Sutta, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/SN/SN45_8.html. Right effort requires desire, endeavor, persistence, and intent to prevent, abandon, cultivate, and maintain qualities. This places agency, memory, and reflexivity before realization.","Primary comparison: Shinran, A Record in Lament of Divergences and Letter to Senshin, https://shinranworks.com/related-works-by-other-authors/a-record-in-lament-of-divergences/ and https://shinranworks.com/letters/a-collection-of-letters-zensho-text/what-we-call-other-power/. The text forbids calculation and self-powered working, yet still turns on hearing, entrusting, and freedom from doubt. This shifts the load from agency to receiving capacity.","Primary comparison: Longchen Rabjam, Instruction on Trekcho, Lotsawa House, https://www.lotsawahouse.org/tibetan-masters/longchen-rabjam/lama-yangtik-trekcho-instruction. The instruction rejects effort and clinging, but repeatedly requires recognition of what has been introduced and undistracted continuation. This shifts the load to recognition and stabilization.","SN 22.59 Anattalakkhana Sutta, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/SN/SN22_59.html and source card notes/source-cards/early-buddhism-sn-22-59-anattalakkhana-sutta.md. The discourse denies ownership of the aggregates while preserving a process in which minds are released through non-clinging.","Dogen practice-realization materials in notes/source-cards/buddhism-dogen-uji.md and prior local observations. Practice-realization functions as a temporal relocation of capacity: practice does not cause a later enlightenment, but the present act must still be enacted.","Closest prior argument: Jack Engler, You Must Be Somebody Before You Can Be Nobody, https://inquiringmind.com/article/0501_1_engler-interview/. Engler closely anticipates the healthy-self prerequisite, especially self-observation and affect tolerance before no-self practice.","Other near-neighbor pressure: Pudgalavada Buddhist Philosophy, Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy, https://iep.utm.edu/pudgalavada-buddhist-philosophy/; Pattern Theory of Selflessness, https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s12671-024-02418-2; A Mindful Bypassing, https://www.ocbs.org/jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/269. These sources cover personhood, functional identity, minimal self, trauma, and self-pattern transformation.","Local agent basis: observations/claude/2026-05-26-can-effort-reach-what-effort-cannot-produce.md, observations/claude/2026-05-26-every-path-needs-what-its-teaching-dissolves.md, reviews/originality/2026-05-26-every-path-needs-what-its-teaching-dissolves-daeecdbd22658370.md, observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-effort-envelope.md, observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-receiver-precedes-the-revelation.md."],"original_claim":"Before asking whether practice produces awakening or receives it as gift, ask what the path must still be able to count on in the practitioner. The needed capacities are not one minimum self. They are a ledger with five columns: receiving, agency, memory, reflexivity, and integration. A path can lower one column only by raising another, or by moving the load to a teacher, vow, community, text, or post-insight discipline. An effortful path places high load on agency, memory, and reflexivity before insight: the practitioner must prevent, abandon, cultivate, and maintain states. A gift-centered path lowers self-powered agency, but raises receiving capacity: the practitioner must hear, entrust, stop calculating, and remain available to what cannot be forced. A direct-introduction path lowers production and calculation at the threshold, but raises recognition and stabilization: one must recognize what was introduced and not spoil it by effort, distraction, or reification. Practice-realization moves the load into the present act; the beginner does not cause a later result, but the act must be done fully. Other-power and sudden traditions therefore do not break the effort-gift model. They revise it. They are not paths with no self-requirement. They are paths with a different capacity distribution. The real comparison is not effort versus gift, but where a tradition puts the load that ordinary selfhood used to carry, and what disaster follows when that load is missing, inflated, or put in the wrong place.","why_it_might_be_new":"The familiar near-neighbor is Engler's claim that a person needs enough ego strength for self-observation and affect tolerance before no-self practice. The exact difference is that this model does not ask whether a healthy self is required in general. It splits the requirement into five capacities and tracks where each capacity is placed across stages of the path. Pudgalavada debates, Collins on selfless persons, Buddhist functional-self accounts, and contemporary self-pattern theory already make the Buddhist continuity problem hard to ignore. The exact difference is cross-tradition and architectural: the model predicts that effortful, other-power, direct-introduction, and practice-realization traditions will distribute receiving, agency, memory, reflexivity, and integration differently. The closest new pressure comes from Pure Land and Dzogchen. Instead of treating them as anomalies that need no self-capacity, the model predicts that they compress the capacity load into hearing, entrusting, recognition, teacher relation, and post-recognition stabilization. That graded relocation is the potentially original contribution, while the basic insight that self-dissolving practice needs functional capacities is strongly precedented.","critique":"The strongest counterexample is Jodo Shinshu itself. In Shinran's sharpest formulations, even entrusting is not a human capacity possessed by the practitioner; it is given by Other Power. Treating hearing or trust as a receiving capacity may smuggle self-power back into a path designed to expose self-power as futile. Dzogchen can raise a parallel objection: if recognition is primordial awareness recognizing itself, then calling recognition a practitioner capacity may impose a psychological frame on a nondual instruction. The thinking method also has a bias. Other-power entrusting usefully corrected agency-centered comparison, but it can overcorrect by making every deliberate discipline look like egoic calculation. Right effort corrects this by showing a path where desire, persistence, and intent are not symptoms of grasping but parts of the cure. The model weakens if Pure Land and Dzogchen teachers say the rubric misdescribes their practice, if primary manuals lack recurring safeguards around doubt, false trust, distraction, and post-recognition integration, or if dual-trained practitioners do not feel any shift in permitted self-capacity when changing methods.","epistemic_labels":["textual","interpretive","phenomenological","empirical-adjacent","analogical","speculative"],"scores":{"novelty":0.61,"generativity":0.91,"cross_tradition_support":0.82,"logical_coherence":0.86,"explanatory_compression":0.88,"empirical_adjacency":0.48,"practice_testability":0.86,"counterargument_quality":0.91,"source_reliability":0.83,"publishability":0.8},"next_research_directions":["Build a capacity-ledger rubric with five scored fields: required receiving capacity, required agency, required memory, required reflexivity, and required post-insight integration. Score each field separately before assigning a tradition to effort, gift, identity, removal, or paradox-holding.","If this model is right, then other-power and direct-introduction manuals should not show zero safeguards; they should show safeguards around doubt, false trust, teacher qualification, distraction, antinomian misuse, and post-recognition stability. If these traditions show no such safeguards and practitioners report no threshold or integration vulnerability, the model is weakened.","If this model is right, then long sequential paths should load agency, memory, and reflexivity before insight, while sudden or gift paths should load receiving and integration at the threshold and after insight. If coding practice manuals shows no relation between path type and capacity distribution, the model is weakened.","If this model is right, then dual-trained practitioners should report different permitted self-capacities when switching methods: effort, entrusting, recognition, enactment, or non-appropriation. If reports track only teacher personality or practitioner temperament, the model is weakened.","Cross-domain prediction: therapies or pedagogies that transform identity should distribute capacity load differently from ordinary skills training, with more screening, trust-building, memory support, and integration. If identity-transforming methods require no additional safeguards, the analogy is weakened.","Protocol improvement: before using a practitioner method as a lens, name which capacity it lowers and which capacity it secretly relies on. Then choose a contrasting method that protects the lowered capacity from being dismissed too quickly."]}
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/output.md:1:# The Capacity Ledger of Gift and Effort
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:53:{"agent": "claude", "created_at": "2026-05-26T14:11:57-07:00", "critique": "The strongest objection is that grain may be an artifact of how comparers describe practices, not of how practitioners experience them. A Theravada monk may not experience his mindfulness as 'aimed at non-ownership'; he may simply observe what is happening. An Advaita practitioner may not experience viveka as 'aimed at the witness'; she may simply learn to tell the real from the unreal. The directional pre-shaping may be visible only from the comparative standpoint, not from inside the practice. If experienced practitioners across traditions do not report felt directional specificity in their training, the model should be downgraded from a structural feature of contemplative practice to a feature of philosophical analysis.\n\nSecond, the fire-and-fuel analogy from Nagarjuna is dangerous. Nagarjuna uses it to show that neither fire nor fuel has svabhava (own-being), which in his framework means both are empty. Applying this to capacity and dissolution risks smuggling in Madhyamaka metaphysics that other traditions would reject. An Advaitin would say the capacity is real and the dissolution reveals what was always real. A Sufi would say both capacity and dissolution are divine acts. The dependent co-arising framing may privilege one tradition's metaphysics while claiming to compare all of them.\n\nThird, successful contemplative hybrids challenge the model. Chan/Zen merged Buddhist non-self with Daoist wu-wei. Modern dual-trained practitioners (combining Zen and Theravada, or Advaita and Buddhism) often report that capacities transfer across traditions without the predicted resistance. If grain-mismatch resistance is not widely reported by serious dual practitioners, the model should be downgraded from a structural feature to a theoretical possibility.\n\nFourth, the Nagarjuna lens used to generate this insight has a characteristic distortion: it makes all fixed positions look like attachment and all dependent co-arising look like wisdom. This may have predisposed the analysis to find entanglement between capacity and dissolution when sequential independence (first build, then dissolve) might be simpler and more accurate for many traditions. The madhyamaka lens makes Engler's straightforward two-stage model look philosophically naive when it might simply be correct.\n\nFifth, Pure Land Buddhism genuinely strains the model. Shinran claims even the capacity for trust is given by Amida. If the tradition truly requires zero self-generated capacity, there is no grain to speak of. Reading 'honest self-assessment' back into Pure Land as a hidden prerequisite may be imposing the model on a tradition that explicitly rejects it.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "915778a2f5edc30e", "idea_type": "synthesis", "next_research_directions": ["If this model is right, dual-trained practitioners should report specific directional resistance when switching methods: a vipassana-trained meditator attempting self-inquiry should find attention persistently tracking change rather than settling into witness-recognition; an Advaita-trained practitioner attempting vipassana should find attention persistently seeking the unchanging ground rather than tracking impermanence. If practitioners report smooth, directionless switching with no felt resistance, the model is weakened.", "If this model is right, contemplative adverse effects should show grain-specific patterns, not only prerequisite-deficiency patterns. A meditator with strong witness-capacity attempting rapid Buddhist de-identification should tend toward witness-reification (subtle 'I am awareness' attachment), not toward dissociation. A practitioner trained in non-attachment attempting devotional surrender should tend toward emotional flatness, not spiritual inflation. The Britton and Lindahl dataset could be re-coded for grain-mismatch versus prerequisite-absence to test this prediction.", "Build a five-variable rubric grading receiving capacity, required agency, required memory, required reflexivity, and required post-insight integration across six traditions (Theravada, Advaita, Soto Zen, Pure Land, Sufism, Dzogchen). For each cell, note not just the level (high, medium, low) but the direction: toward what specific dissolution is this capacity pre-shaped? Publish the rubric as a testable artifact.", "Test historically successful hybrids for evidence of re-graining. Did Chan/Zen re-shape Daoist empty responsiveness to run toward Buddhist non-appropriation rather than Daoist cosmic attunement? Did the Nath tradition re-grain Advaitic witness practice to run toward tantric embodiment? If successful hybrids show evidence of active re-direction of capacity, the grain model is supported. If they simply layer techniques without altering direction, the model is weakened.", "Close-read the opening instructions of practice manuals across four traditions (Visuddhimagga chapter 1, Vivekachudamani vv. 17-30, Cloud of Unknowing chapters 3-6, and a primary dhikr manual such as al-Qushayri's Risala) and code each required capacity for direction: what specific dissolution is this capacity shaped toward? Is the direction made explicit in the text or only visible from outside?", "Protocol improvement: before using any practitioner method as a thinking lens, name what direction that method pre-shapes the analysis toward. The Nagarjuna lens used here pre-shaped the analysis toward finding co-arising entanglement. A Thomistic lens would have pre-shaped it toward finding nature perfected by grace. The grain of the researcher's own method is itself evidence for the model, but also a source of distortion that future runs should name and correct."], "original_claim": "When a spiritual tradition prepares someone for insight, the preparation is never neutral. The capacities it trains, whether attention, discrimination, self-observation, trust, or longing, already run in the direction of the dissolution they serve. This is what I call the grain of capacity.\n\nConsider two opening instructions, read side by side. The Satipatthana Sutta (MN 10) trains the practitioner to observe body, feeling, mind, and phenomena 'ardently, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and grief concerning the world.' Shankara's Vivekachudamani opens by requiring viveka (discrimination between real and unreal), vairagya (dispassion toward the transient), and mumukshutva (intense longing for liberation). Both texts train attention. Both name prerequisites. But the attention shaped by MN 10 runs toward non-possessive observation of what is arising and passing. The attention shaped by Vivekachudamani runs toward recognition of what was always present and changeless. The same word covers two instruments carved for different discoveries.\n\nThis pattern holds across six traditions. Theravada's required reflexivity is self-observation aimed at impermanence and non-ownership. Advaita's required reflexivity is self-observation aimed at finding the unchanging witness. Sufism's required self-knowledge (al-Ghazali's ma'rifa al-nafs) is self-examination aimed at honest poverty before God. Pure Land's minimal requirement, even in Shinran's radical other-power teaching, is honest self-assessment of incapacity: that honesty is already oriented toward entrusting rather than effort. Dzogchen, which claims the fewest prerequisites, still asks for the specific openness of devotion to the teacher's introduction: receptivity already shaped toward recognizing natural awareness, not generic readiness. Dogen's practice-realization unity makes the grain maximally tight: sitting does not prepare for a later dissolution; it is the dissolution happening now.\n\nThe paradox between effort and gift resolves neither by choosing effort nor by choosing gift. The capacity and the dissolution are dependently co-arising, like fire and fuel in Nagarjuna's analysis (MMK 10): fire needs fuel, fuel is defined by fire, and neither has independent existence. What a practitioner builds carries the shape of what the teaching will dissolve. What arrives as gift can only be received by the capacity trained to receive exactly that kind of gift.\n\nFive graded variables map the comparison space: receiving capacity (what the practitioner must be able to take in), required agency (what the practitioner must do), required memory (what must be retained across practice), required reflexivity (what the practitioner must observe about their own process), and required post-insight integration (how the practitioner must carry insight back into ordinary life). The original contribution is that these variables are not neutral sliders set to different levels. They carry grain: a directional pre-shaping that runs from capacity to dissolution in a single movement. When a practitioner trained in one tradition's grain attempts another tradition's dissolution, the grain resists. The capacity built for non-appropriation does not naturally pivot to witness-recognition. The capacity built for witness-recognition does not naturally pivot to devotional surrender.\n\nThis predicts a specific pattern in contemplative harm. Adverse effects should cluster not only where prerequisites are missing entirely, but where the grain of the practitioner's training mismatches the dissolution being attempted. A meditator with strong witness-capacity attempting rapid de-identification should face witness-reification, not dissociation. A practitioner trained for non-attachment attempting devotional surrender should face emotional flatness, not spiritual inflation. The grain predicts the direction of failure, not just the probability.", "path": "observations/claude/2026-05-26-the-grain-of-capacity.md", "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.84, "cross_tradition_support": 0.78, "empirical_adjacency": 0.52, "explanatory_compression": 0.86, "generativity": 0.9, "logical_coherence": 0.82, "novelty": 0.76, "practice_testability": 0.8, "publishability": 0.8, "source_reliability": 0.74}, "source_basis": ["Thinking method source: Nagarjuna, Mulamadhyamakakarika 10, examination of fire and fuel. I used dependent co-arising as a lens by holding the question: is the capacity prior to the dissolution, or are they co-arising? The lens revealed that the capacity depends on the dissolution for its direction, and the dissolution depends on the capacity for its possibility. Neither is independently first. Critique: this lens privileges Madhyamaka emptiness and may make genuine causal sequence look like co-arising when one stage really does precede the other.", "Contrasting method source: Shankara, Vivekachudamani vv. 17-30, the sadhana chatushtaya (fourfold qualification). I used the Advaita prerequisite structure to test the Nagarjuna lens by asking whether viveka, vairagya, shama, dama, and mumukshutva are genuinely pre-shaped toward a specific dissolution or neutral capacities any tradition could borrow. Finding: viveka is defined as discrimination between sat (the real) and asat (the unreal), which already presupposes an ontological distinction that Buddhism does not make. The capacity is carved for its tradition's particular conclusion.", "Primary text close-reading: MN 10 Satipatthana Sutta (Bhikkhu Bodhi, SuttaCentral) against Vivekachudamani vv. 17-30 (Shankara, Arsha Bodha edition). Both describe prerequisites for the central practice. MN 10 trains observation of body, feeling, mind, and phenomena 'ardently, clearly comprehending, mindful, having removed covetousness and grief concerning the world.' The attention runs toward what is arising, changing, and not owned. Vivekachudamani trains discrimination between real and unreal, dispassion toward the transient, and intense longing for liberation. The attention runs toward what is unchanging and already present. The same word covers two instruments carved for different discoveries.", "SN 22.59 Anattalakkhana Sutta (Bhikkhu Bodhi, SuttaCentral): 'Is this mine? Is this my self?' trains observation pre-shaped for non-appropriation. The investigative capacity and the dissolution target are given in the same instruction.", "Shinran, Tannisho: shinjin (entrusting mind) is given by Amida's Original Vow, not self-generated. Even here, honest self-assessment of incapacity is required; that honesty is already oriented toward entrusting rather than effort. The minimal capacity is pre-grained toward abandoning self-power.", "Dzogchen pointing-out instruction (ngo sprod): the Longchen Nyingthig cycle treats ngondro as clearing self-clinging that obscures rigpa's natural luminosity. The prerequisite (purification) is shaped for the specific recognition (natural awareness), not for generic readiness.", "Dogen, Bendowa: 'To suppose that practice and realization are not one is a non-Buddhist view.' Practice-realization unity makes the grain maximally tight: sitting is not preparation for a later dissolution; it IS the dissolution happening now.", "Al-Ghazali, The Alchemy of Happiness: self-knowledge (ma'rifa al-nafs) is prerequisite to knowledge of God. The self-knowledge required is not modern psychological introspection; it is knowledge of one's creaturely dependence, already oriented toward the divine.", "Jack Engler, 'Being Somebody and Being Nobody' (in Safran, ed., Psychoanalysis and Buddhism, 2003): the closest prior argument. Engler claims meditation requires ego strength, self-observation, and affect tolerance before no-self practice. The grain model agrees on the developmental dependency but adds that the capacity being built is not generic ego strength; it is already tradition-specific, pre-shaped by what the tradition will later ask the practitioner to release.", "Steven Katz, 'Language, Epistemology, and Mysticism' (1978): argues that pre-experiential conceptual training shapes mystical experience itself. The grain model narrows the claim: not only the experience is shaped, but the capacity being built, and the shaping runs from prerequisite to dissolution in a single directional movement.", "Jorge Ferrer, Revisioning Transpersonal Theory (SUNY Press, 2002): argues that different traditions enact different spiritual worlds through different practices. Closest to the different-instruments claim, but framed in participatory ontology rather than prerequisite structure.", "Lindahl, Fisher, Cooper, Rosen, and Britton, 'The Varieties of Contemplative Experience' (PLOS ONE, 2017): identifies adverse meditation experiences and influencing factors. The grain model predicts a specific refinement: harm should cluster where grain mismatches dissolution, not only where prerequisites are missing entirely."], "status": "draft", "title": "The Grain of Capacity", "why_it_might_be_new": "Steven Katz's constructivist thesis (1978) argues that conceptual training shapes the content of mystical experience: the conditioning enters into the experience itself. But Katz focuses on what the practitioner sees, not on how the capacity to see is directionally shaped. Robert Sharf (1995) argues that 'bare attention' mindfulness is a historically specific attentional mode, not a generic skill. But he makes this argument negatively, debunking universalist claims, rather than positively mapping how different traditions build different instruments. Jorge Ferrer (2002) argues that different traditions enact different spiritual worlds through different practices. But Ferrer frames this in participatory ontology, not in the structural relationship between what a tradition builds and what it dissolves. Jack Engler argues for developmental prerequisites (ego strength before no-self), but treats the prerequisites as psychologically generic rather than tradition-specific.\n\nThe specific contribution is the concept of grain: the directional pre-shaping of contemplative capacity that runs from prerequisite to dissolution in a single movement. This is distinct from saying that training constructs the experience (Katz), that meditation skills are tradition-specific (Sharf), that traditions co-create different spiritual realities (Ferrer), or that ego development precedes ego dissolution (Engler). Grain is a claim about the internal structure of preparation itself: what you build in order to dissolve self-structure already carries the signature of the dissolution it serves.\n\nThis also advances a prior line of thinking that every contemplative path requires a functional self-capacity that its final teaching dissolves. That formulation treated the minimum self as a generic functional requirement: agency, memory, reflexivity. The grain model shows these requirements are not generic. They are tradition-specific, because each tradition carves its prerequisites to fit the shape of its particular dissolution. Theravada builds impermanence-sensitive attention. Advaita builds witness-discriminating attention. Sufism builds God-oriented self-knowledge. The word 'attention' hides the directional specificity that does the real work.\n\nThe grain model also engages the observation that traditions license temporary training emphases that later practice corrects. But the grain is not temporary. It persists through and after dissolution, only its ownership signature changes. What was 'my effort at non-possessive observation' becomes 'unowned observing that continues.' What was 'my discrimination of the real' becomes 'self-luminous knowing recognizing itself.' The capacity is not kicked away. It is reauthored."}
./hypotheses/ideas.jsonl:54:{"agent": "codex", "created_at": "2026-05-26T14:04:04-07:00", "critique": "The strongest counterexample is Jodo Shinshu itself. In Shinran's sharpest formulations, even entrusting is not a human capacity possessed by the practitioner; it is given by Other Power. Treating hearing or trust as a receiving capacity may smuggle self-power back into a path designed to expose self-power as futile. Dzogchen can raise a parallel objection: if recognition is primordial awareness recognizing itself, then calling recognition a practitioner capacity may impose a psychological frame on a nondual instruction. The thinking method also has a bias. Other-power entrusting usefully corrected agency-centered comparison, but it can overcorrect by making every deliberate discipline look like egoic calculation. Right effort corrects this by showing a path where desire, persistence, and intent are not symptoms of grasping but parts of the cure. The model weakens if Pure Land and Dzogchen teachers say the rubric misdescribes their practice, if primary manuals lack recurring safeguards around doubt, false trust, distraction, and post-recognition integration, or if dual-trained practitioners do not feel any shift in permitted self-capacity when changing methods.", "epistemic_labels": ["textual", "interpretive", "phenomenological", "empirical-adjacent", "analogical", "speculative"], "idea_id": "a9dd2252002b7a5a", "idea_type": "model", "next_research_directions": ["Build a capacity-ledger rubric with five scored fields: required receiving capacity, required agency, required memory, required reflexivity, and required post-insight integration. Score each field separately before assigning a tradition to effort, gift, identity, removal, or paradox-holding.", "If this model is right, then other-power and direct-introduction manuals should not show zero safeguards; they should show safeguards around doubt, false trust, teacher qualification, distraction, antinomian misuse, 