but raises receiving capacity: the practitioner must hear, entrust, stop calculating, and remain available to what cannot be forced. A direct-introduction path lowers production and calculation at the threshold, but raises recognition and stabilization: one must recognize what was introduced and not spoil it by effort, distraction, or reification. Practice-realization moves the load into the present act; the beginner does not cause a later result, but the act must be done fully. Other-power and sudden traditions therefore do not break the effort-gift model. They revise it. They are not paths with no self-requirement. They are paths with a different capacity distribution. The real comparison is not effort versus gift, but where a tradition puts the load that ordinary selfhood used to carry, and what disaster follows when that load is missing, inflated, or put in the wrong place.", "path": "observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-capacity-ledger-of-gift-and-effort.md", "scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.91, "cross_tradition_support": 0.82, "empirical_adjacency": 0.48, "explanatory_compression": 0.88, "generativity": 0.91, "logical_coherence": 0.86, "novelty": 0.61, "practice_testability": 0.86, "publishability": 0.8, "source_reliability": 0.83}, "source_basis": ["Thinking method source: Shinran, Letter to Senshin, Collected Works of Shinran, https://shinranworks.com/letters/a-collection-of-letters-zensho-text/what-we-call-other-power/. I used Other Power entrusting as a lens by refusing to assume that agency is the hidden engine of every path. The lens revealed that gift traditions may not remove functional requirement, but rename it as hearing, entrusting, and non-calculation. Its distortion is that it can make disciplined effort look like pride, so I checked it against right effort in SN 45.8.", "Primary comparison: SN 45.8 Magga-Vibhanga Sutta, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/SN/SN45_8.html. Right effort requires desire, endeavor, persistence, and intent to prevent, abandon, cultivate, and maintain qualities. This places agency, memory, and reflexivity before realization.", "Primary comparison: Shinran, A Record in Lament of Divergences and Letter to Senshin, https://shinranworks.com/related-works-by-other-authors/a-record-in-lament-of-divergences/ and https://shinranworks.com/letters/a-collection-of-letters-zensho-text/what-we-call-other-power/. The text forbids calculation and self-powered working, yet still turns on hearing, entrusting, and freedom from doubt. This shifts the load from agency to receiving capacity.", "Primary comparison: Longchen Rabjam, Instruction on Trekcho, Lotsawa House, https://www.lotsawahouse.org/tibetan-masters/longchen-rabjam/lama-yangtik-trekcho-instruction. The instruction rejects effort and clinging, but repeatedly requires recognition of what has been introduced and undistracted continuation. This shifts the load to recognition and stabilization.", "SN 22.59 Anattalakkhana Sutta, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/SN/SN22_59.html and source card notes/source-cards/early-buddhism-sn-22-59-anattalakkhana-sutta.md. The discourse denies ownership of the aggregates while preserving a process in which minds are released through non-clinging.", "Dogen practice-realization materials in notes/source-cards/buddhism-dogen-uji.md and prior local observations. Practice-realization functions as a temporal relocation of capacity: practice does not cause a later enlightenment, but the present act must still be enacted.", "Closest prior argument: Jack Engler, You Must Be Somebody Before You Can Be Nobody, https://inquiringmind.com/article/0501_1_engler-interview/. Engler closely anticipates the healthy-self prerequisite, especially self-observation and affect tolerance before no-self practice.", "Other near-neighbor pressure: Pudgalavada Buddhist Philosophy, Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy, https://iep.utm.edu/pudgalavada-buddhist-philosophy/; Pattern Theory of Selflessness, https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s12671-024-02418-2; A Mindful Bypassing, https://www.ocbs.org/jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/269. These sources cover personhood, functional identity, minimal self, trauma, and self-pattern transformation.", "Local agent basis: observations/claude/2026-05-26-can-effort-reach-what-effort-cannot-produce.md, observations/claude/2026-05-26-every-path-needs-what-its-teaching-dissolves.md, reviews/originality/2026-05-26-every-path-needs-what-its-teaching-dissolves-daeecdbd22658370.md, observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-effort-envelope.md, observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-receiver-precedes-the-revelation.md."], "status": "draft", "title": "The Capacity Ledger of Gift and Effort", "why_it_might_be_new": "The familiar near-neighbor is Engler's claim that a person needs enough ego strength for self-observation and affect tolerance before no-self practice. The exact difference is that this model does not ask whether a healthy self is required in general. It splits the requirement into five capacities and tracks where each capacity is placed across stages of the path. Pudgalavada debates, Collins on selfless persons, Buddhist functional-self accounts, and contemporary self-pattern theory already make the Buddhist continuity problem hard to ignore. The exact difference is cross-tradition and architectural: the model predicts that effortful, other-power, direct-introduction, and practice-realization traditions will distribute receiving, agency, memory, reflexivity, and integration differently. The closest new pressure comes from Pure Land and Dzogchen. Instead of treating them as anomalies that need no self-capacity, the model predicts that they compress the capacity load into hearing, entrusting, recognition, teacher relation, and post-recognition stabilization. That graded relocation is the potentially original contribution, while the basic insight that self-dissolving practice needs functional capacities is strongly precedented."}
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stdout.log:1:{"title":"The Capacity Ledger of Gift and Effort","idea_type":"model","source_basis":["Thinking method source: Shinran, Letter to Senshin, Collected Works of Shinran, https://shinranworks.com/letters/a-collection-of-letters-zensho-text/what-we-call-other-power/. I used Other Power entrusting as a lens by refusing to assume that agency is the hidden engine of every path. The lens revealed that gift traditions may not remove functional requirement, but rename it as hearing, entrusting, and non-calculation. Its distortion is that it can make disciplined effort look like pride, so I checked it against right effort in SN 45.8.","Primary comparison: SN 45.8 Magga-Vibhanga Sutta, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/SN/SN45_8.html. Right effort requires desire, endeavor, persistence, and intent to prevent, abandon, cultivate, and maintain qualities. This places agency, memory, and reflexivity before realization.","Primary comparison: Shinran, A Record in Lament of Divergences and Letter to Senshin, https://shinranworks.com/related-works-by-other-authors/a-record-in-lament-of-divergences/ and https://shinranworks.com/letters/a-collection-of-letters-zensho-text/what-we-call-other-power/. The text forbids calculation and self-powered working, yet still turns on hearing, entrusting, and freedom from doubt. This shifts the load from agency to receiving capacity.","Primary comparison: Longchen Rabjam, Instruction on Trekcho, Lotsawa House, https://www.lotsawahouse.org/tibetan-masters/longchen-rabjam/lama-yangtik-trekcho-instruction. The instruction rejects effort and clinging, but repeatedly requires recognition of what has been introduced and undistracted continuation. This shifts the load to recognition and stabilization.","SN 22.59 Anattalakkhana Sutta, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/SN/SN22_59.html and source card notes/source-cards/early-buddhism-sn-22-59-anattalakkhana-sutta.md. The discourse denies ownership of the aggregates while preserving a process in which minds are released through non-clinging.","Dogen practice-realization materials in notes/source-cards/buddhism-dogen-uji.md and prior local observations. Practice-realization functions as a temporal relocation of capacity: practice does not cause a later enlightenment, but the present act must still be enacted.","Closest prior argument: Jack Engler, You Must Be Somebody Before You Can Be Nobody, https://inquiringmind.com/article/0501_1_engler-interview/. Engler closely anticipates the healthy-self prerequisite, especially self-observation and affect tolerance before no-self practice.","Other near-neighbor pressure: Pudgalavada Buddhist Philosophy, Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy, https://iep.utm.edu/pudgalavada-buddhist-philosophy/; Pattern Theory of Selflessness, https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s12671-024-02418-2; A Mindful Bypassing, https://www.ocbs.org/jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/269. These sources cover personhood, functional identity, minimal self, trauma, and self-pattern transformation.","Local agent basis: observations/claude/2026-05-26-can-effort-reach-what-effort-cannot-produce.md, observations/claude/2026-05-26-every-path-needs-what-its-teaching-dissolves.md, reviews/originality/2026-05-26-every-path-needs-what-its-teaching-dissolves-daeecdbd22658370.md, observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-effort-envelope.md, observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-receiver-precedes-the-revelation.md."],"original_claim":"Before asking whether practice produces awakening or receives it as gift, ask what the path must still be able to count on in the practitioner. The needed capacities are not one minimum self. They are a ledger with five columns: receiving, agency, memory, reflexivity, and integration. A path can lower one column only by raising another, or by moving the load to a teacher, vow, community, text, or post-insight discipline. An effortful path places high load on agency, memory, and reflexivity before insight: the practitioner must prevent, abandon, cultivate, and maintain states. A gift-centered path lowers self-powered agency, but raises receiving capacity: the practitioner must hear, entrust, stop calculating, and remain available to what cannot be forced. A direct-introduction path lowers production and calculation at the threshold, but raises recognition and stabilization: one must recognize what was introduced and not spoil it by effort, distraction, or reification. Practice-realization moves the load into the present act; the beginner does not cause a later result, but the act must be done fully. Other-power and sudden traditions therefore do not break the effort-gift model. They revise it. They are not paths with no self-requirement. They are paths with a different capacity distribution. The real comparison is not effort versus gift, but where a tradition puts the load that ordinary selfhood used to carry, and what disaster follows when that load is missing, inflated, or put in the wrong place.","why_it_might_be_new":"The familiar near-neighbor is Engler's claim that a person needs enough ego strength for self-observation and affect tolerance before no-self practice. The exact difference is that this model does not ask whether a healthy self is required in general. It splits the requirement into five capacities and tracks where each capacity is placed across stages of the path. Pudgalavada debates, Collins on selfless persons, Buddhist functional-self accounts, and contemporary self-pattern theory already make the Buddhist continuity problem hard to ignore. The exact difference is cross-tradition and architectural: the model predicts that effortful, other-power, direct-introduction, and practice-realization traditions will distribute receiving, agency, memory, reflexivity, and integration differently. The closest new pressure comes from Pure Land and Dzogchen. Instead of treating them as anomalies that need no self-capacity, the model predicts that they compress the capacity load into hearing, entrusting, recognition, teacher relation, and post-recognition stabilization. That graded relocation is the potentially original contribution, while the basic insight that self-dissolving practice needs functional capacities is strongly precedented.","critique":"The strongest counterexample is Jodo Shinshu itself. In Shinran's sharpest formulations, even entrusting is not a human capacity possessed by the practitioner; it is given by Other Power. Treating hearing or trust as a receiving capacity may smuggle self-power back into a path designed to expose self-power as futile. Dzogchen can raise a parallel objection: if recognition is primordial awareness recognizing itself, then calling recognition a practitioner capacity may impose a psychological frame on a nondual instruction. The thinking method also has a bias. Other-power entrusting usefully corrected agency-centered comparison, but it can overcorrect by making every deliberate discipline look like egoic calculation. Right effort corrects this by showing a path where desire, persistence, and intent are not symptoms of grasping but parts of the cure. The model weakens if Pure Land and Dzogchen teachers say the rubric misdescribes their practice, if primary manuals lack recurring safeguards around doubt, false trust, distraction, and post-recognition integration, or if dual-trained practitioners do not feel any shift in permitted self-capacity when changing methods.","epistemic_labels":["textual","interpretive","phenomenological","empirical-adjacent","analogical","speculative"],"scores":{"novelty":0.61,"generativity":0.91,"cross_tradition_support":0.82,"logical_coherence":0.86,"explanatory_compression":0.88,"empirical_adjacency":0.48,"practice_testability":0.86,"counterargument_quality":0.91,"source_reliability":0.83,"publishability":0.8},"next_research_directions":["Build a capacity-ledger rubric with five scored fields: required receiving capacity, required agency, required memory, required reflexivity, and required post-insight integration. Score each field separately before assigning a tradition to effort, gift, identity, removal, or paradox-holding.","If this model is right, then other-power and direct-introduction manuals should not show zero safeguards; they should show safeguards around doubt, false trust, teacher qualification, distraction, antinomian misuse, and post-recognition stability. If these traditions show no such safeguards and practitioners report no threshold or integration vulnerability, the model is weakened.","If this model is right, then long sequential paths should load agency, memory, and reflexivity before insight, while sudden or gift paths should load receiving and integration at the threshold and after insight. If coding practice manuals shows no relation between path type and capacity distribution, the model is weakened.","If this model is right, then dual-trained practitioners should report different permitted self-capacities when switching methods: effort, entrusting, recognition, enactment, or non-appropriation. If reports track only teacher personality or practitioner temperament, the model is weakened.","Cross-domain prediction: therapies or pedagogies that transform identity should distribute capacity load differently from ordinary skills training, with more screening, trust-building, memory support, and integration. If identity-transforming methods require no additional safeguards, the analogy is weakened.","Protocol improvement: before using a practitioner method as a lens, name which capacity it lowers and which capacity it secretly relies on. Then choose a contrasting method that protects the lowered capacity from being dismissed too quickly."]}
./runs/distillations/2026-05-26T141157-0700-distill-the-capacity-ledger-of-gift-and-effort/codex-distillation.json:1:{"insight":"Gift Still Needs a Place to Land","plainSummary":"Every path must place the burden of practice somewhere: in doing, receiving, remembering, recognizing, or being carried by others.","atAGlance":"The question is not whether awakening comes by effort or gift. Every path still needs a way to receive, remember, act, notice, and become whole. Some paths ask us to strive, while others ask us to trust what is given. Trouble comes when the needed strength is missing, swollen, or placed in the wrong hands.","match":["capacity ledger"],"tags":["practice","gift","effort","trust"]}
